51
00:03:29,709 --> 00:03:32,159
It is where the legal
relationship is created.

52
00:03:32,769 --> 00:03:35,160
It is where consent
boundaries are defined.

53
00:03:35,919 --> 00:03:39,769
It is where a customer is granted
access to regulated services.

54
00:03:40,650 --> 00:03:45,559
Every field they fill in, every
disclosure they see, every box

55
00:03:45,699 --> 00:03:48,379
they tick, these have legal weight.

56
00:03:48,879 --> 00:03:52,659
They create a record that may
need to be proceed years later.

57
00:03:53,159 --> 00:03:55,089
A misdisclosure is not a bug.

58
00:03:55,459 --> 00:03:59,909
It is a compliance event, and this
is fundamentally different problem

59
00:03:59,909 --> 00:04:05,129
to solve, which means it needs
fundamentally different design approach.

60
00:04:05,629 --> 00:04:10,999
So what does it look like when a
platform was not built with this in mind?

61
00:04:11,499 --> 00:04:16,729
The platform I see most often is what
I call after-the-thought problem.

62
00:04:17,709 --> 00:04:21,649
Compliance gets treated as a
documentation, something you add

63
00:04:21,719 --> 00:04:23,759
after the legal design work is done.

64
00:04:24,259 --> 00:04:29,249
You build a feature, ship it, get
a legal review, someone writes up a

65
00:04:29,249 --> 00:04:32,559
control document, and it feels handled.

66
00:04:33,059 --> 00:04:34,359
Until it is not.

67
00:04:34,859 --> 00:04:39,469
When an audit arise, you are manually
pulling evidence from scattered

68
00:04:39,469 --> 00:04:45,149
logs, old emails, Confluence pages
written by people who may not

69
00:04:45,219 --> 00:04:47,329
even at the to company anymore.

70
00:04:47,829 --> 00:04:53,629
It takes a weeks, it is stressful,
and you are never fully sure if

71
00:04:53,629 --> 00:04:55,479
what you have assembled is complete.

72
00:04:55,979 --> 00:05:00,289
When a dispute comes in, nobody
can say with the real confidence

73
00:05:00,489 --> 00:05:05,979
what the customer actually saw or
what they agreed to exactly when.

74
00:05:06,479 --> 00:05:12,409
Then the specific failure pattern I want
to name this is the treating compliance

75
00:05:12,409 --> 00:05:18,259
as a surface layer, as a set of UI
components, checkboxes, models, form

76
00:05:18,259 --> 00:05:24,409
validation The problem with a checkbox
is that it can be changed, skipped,

77
00:05:24,729 --> 00:05:28,989
broken, or deployed in a version that
does not actually record anything.

78
00:05:29,979 --> 00:05:34,939
A checkbox is not a guarantee, and I
have seen this happen in a real systems.

79
00:05:35,659 --> 00:05:40,689
The checkbox existed, the UI looked
correct, but when the audit question

80
00:05:40,689 --> 00:05:45,969
started, there was no reliable record of
what the customer had actually agreed to.

81
00:05:46,469 --> 00:05:50,669
Everything that follows is what
the shift looks like in a practice.

82
00:05:51,169 --> 00:05:57,099
Here is the core idea of the talk,
and it sounds simple, but I want to be

83
00:05:57,099 --> 00:05:59,549
clear about how big of the shift it is.

84
00:06:00,299 --> 00:06:01,579
Compliance is not a layer.

85
00:06:01,819 --> 00:06:02,869
It is a checklist.

86
00:06:02,929 --> 00:06:04,089
It is not a checklist.

87
00:06:04,409 --> 00:06:09,339
It is not something the legal team
owns and engineering works around.

88
00:06:09,839 --> 00:06:15,399
What that means in a concrete terms,
regulatory requirement stop being you

89
00:06:16,349 --> 00:06:18,699
right up after design decisions are made.

90
00:06:19,309 --> 00:06:24,119
They become the constraints that shape
those decisions from the very beginning.

91
00:06:24,619 --> 00:06:28,569
Before, compliance is the
documentation added after the fact.

92
00:06:29,129 --> 00:06:34,089
After, compliance is architecture
built into every constraint, every

93
00:06:34,089 --> 00:06:36,789
boundary, every control from day one.

94
00:06:37,289 --> 00:06:42,399
That is a simple forming, but implementing
it changes everything about how you build.

95
00:06:42,869 --> 00:06:45,589
Let me show you what it looks like.

96
00:06:46,089 --> 00:06:51,419
This is a slide I want you to take
as a photo of if you take anything

97
00:06:51,419 --> 00:06:55,459
from today because this is the
mental model that changes how you

98
00:06:55,499 --> 00:06:57,819
approach building regulated platforms.

99
00:06:58,729 --> 00:07:02,989
Every regulated obligations has a
direct architecture counterpart.

100
00:07:03,399 --> 00:07:07,619
Not a policy, not a process,
a concrete system constraint.

101
00:07:08,529 --> 00:07:11,349
Something the system
enforces, not the team.

102
00:07:11,849 --> 00:07:13,889
Informed consent requirement.

103
00:07:14,709 --> 00:07:19,079
The counterpart is not a policy that
says get consent before proceeding.

104
00:07:19,949 --> 00:07:23,789
It is consent capture embedded
in the interaction flow, where

105
00:07:23,789 --> 00:07:27,899
the system literally cannot move
to the next step without it.

106
00:07:28,399 --> 00:07:33,569
Disclosure at the point of decision,
the counterpart, the API enforces the

107
00:07:33,569 --> 00:07:38,069
disclosure before the action runs,
not before it should, before it can.

108
00:07:38,599 --> 00:07:40,399
Those two phases sound similar.

109
00:07:40,859 --> 00:07:43,319
They are completely different guarantees.

110
00:07:43,819 --> 00:07:48,839
Once you start thinking this way,
regulations stop looking like external

111
00:07:48,839 --> 00:07:53,379
policy document and start looking
like direct architectural requirement.

112
00:07:54,039 --> 00:07:57,939
That shift in the thinking changes
everything about how you design.

113
00:07:58,859 --> 00:08:04,679
To explanation, a decision trail generated
at runtime automatically Every time.

114
00:08:05,259 --> 00:08:06,179
Record retention.

115
00:08:06,579 --> 00:08:12,289
Not a backup, but an immutable open,
only event store per interaction.

116
00:08:12,789 --> 00:08:16,949
I want to introduce the concept
that ties everything together and

117
00:08:16,949 --> 00:08:18,949
that I call interaction integrity.

118
00:08:19,449 --> 00:08:24,859
Interaction integrity is the property
of onboarding flows where every material

119
00:08:24,859 --> 00:08:30,629
interaction is structured, versions and
evidence producing, not as a side effect,

120
00:08:31,159 --> 00:08:34,569
but as a designed first-class output.

121
00:08:35,069 --> 00:08:39,880
I build this on three pillars, and we are
going to walk through each one in detail.

122
00:08:40,389 --> 00:08:44,250
Pillar one, consent and disclosure
as compliance artifacts.

123
00:08:44,720 --> 00:08:47,929
The pillar two, identity assurance.

124
00:08:48,429 --> 00:08:52,709
And pillar three, exception
handling and interaction continuity.

125
00:08:53,209 --> 00:08:57,069
Pillar one, consent and disclosure
as compliance artifacts.

126
00:08:57,809 --> 00:09:03,349
The way most platform handle consent today
is by capturing it as a thin UI logic.

127
00:09:03,849 --> 00:09:07,899
A checkbox or a model that is
completely disconnected from

128
00:09:07,899 --> 00:09:09,289
the audit system underneath.

129
00:09:10,049 --> 00:09:11,369
It is legally fragile.

130
00:09:12,009 --> 00:09:15,309
It can be break without
the audit record knowing.

131
00:09:15,889 --> 00:09:19,959
The compliant design treats
every consent, the interactions

132
00:09:19,999 --> 00:09:22,029
as a formal defined artifact.

133
00:09:22,939 --> 00:09:25,009
An object that carries four things.

134
00:09:25,509 --> 00:09:30,989
The version of the disclosure that
has shown, not the terms, the exact

135
00:09:30,989 --> 00:09:36,429
version, the timestamp of when it
was presented, the user's explicit

136
00:09:36,429 --> 00:09:41,019
response, and the state of the system
at the exact moment of the interaction.

137
00:09:41,989 --> 00:09:45,769
You can see the right side of
the slide shows what that looks

138
00:09:45,769 --> 00:09:47,269
like an actual data field.

139
00:09:47,769 --> 00:09:49,089
This is not abstract.

140
00:09:49,769 --> 00:09:53,639
It is a design contract with the
specific required properties.

141
00:09:54,139 --> 00:09:57,589
Let me go one level deeper on
how you actually build this.

142
00:09:58,389 --> 00:10:03,779
Disclosure content is managed as
versioned, uniquely addressable artifacts.

143
00:10:04,609 --> 00:10:09,629
When a regulation changes and the
terms need updating, you don't, you

144
00:10:09,629 --> 00:10:11,659
do not overwrite the old version.

145
00:10:12,499 --> 00:10:16,099
You add a new changes, a new one.

146
00:10:16,859 --> 00:10:21,989
Any historical interaction can always
be resolved back to the exact text

147
00:10:21,989 --> 00:10:24,439
to the customer s- at the moment.

148
00:10:25,319 --> 00:10:31,039
Content events are emitted as immutable
records into an append-only log.

149
00:10:31,489 --> 00:10:33,029
The record is written once.

150
00:10:33,109 --> 00:10:34,649
It is never modified.

151
00:10:35,339 --> 00:10:38,909
The audit trail is permanently by design.

152
00:10:39,409 --> 00:10:42,844
This is the difference
between a log and evidence.

153
00:10:43,224 --> 00:10:45,204
A log records what happened.

154
00:10:45,704 --> 00:10:49,494
Evidence produces something that
can be used to prove what happened

155
00:10:50,454 --> 00:10:53,194
with the certainty under scrutiny.

156
00:10:54,154 --> 00:11:00,864
The practice tools of this, Apache
Kafka for the event stream, AWS S3 with

157
00:11:00,904 --> 00:11:03,444
object log for the immutable storage.

158
00:11:03,944 --> 00:11:07,524
These are listed on the architecture
slide coming up shortly.

159
00:11:08,024 --> 00:11:10,724
This is the most important
slide in the pillar one.

160
00:11:11,394 --> 00:11:13,154
Consent is not a checkbox.

161
00:11:13,714 --> 00:11:14,944
It is a system event.

162
00:11:15,864 --> 00:11:17,684
The sequence has the three steps.

163
00:11:18,234 --> 00:11:22,224
They must happen in order, no
skipping, no running them in parallel.

164
00:11:22,724 --> 00:11:24,924
Step one, disclose.

165
00:11:25,514 --> 00:11:30,634
Terms, version number, channel
context, all presented to the user

166
00:11:30,634 --> 00:11:32,834
explicitly with the version tracked.

167
00:11:33,494 --> 00:11:35,484
Step two, acknowledge.

168
00:11:36,234 --> 00:11:41,134
The user's explicit response is
captured as a system event, not a

169
00:11:41,234 --> 00:11:42,944
click tracked in analytical tool.

170
00:11:43,654 --> 00:11:47,934
A platform record with its own
timestamp and reference to the

171
00:11:48,014 --> 00:11:49,954
exact version of the terms they saw.

172
00:11:50,954 --> 00:11:52,564
Step three, act.

173
00:11:53,014 --> 00:11:57,174
The action proceeds only after
the gate is satisfied, not before,

174
00:11:57,794 --> 00:12:00,394
not at the same time, after.

175
00:12:01,014 --> 00:12:06,094
This is the difference between a
client and evidence, and in a regulated

176
00:12:06,094 --> 00:12:08,854
environment, the difference is everything.

177
00:12:09,354 --> 00:12:12,694
Pillar two, progressive
identity assurance.

178
00:12:13,474 --> 00:12:17,524
Identity checking is not a
binary gate, pass or fail.

179
00:12:18,294 --> 00:12:21,854
In a well-designed system,
it is a risk adjustment.

180
00:12:21,924 --> 00:12:23,474
It builds up gradually.

181
00:12:23,974 --> 00:12:25,514
Low-risk access first.

182
00:12:25,984 --> 00:12:30,504
The customer can interact with
limited features while identity

183
00:12:30,554 --> 00:12:32,164
is still being confirmed.

184
00:12:32,664 --> 00:12:34,444
Verification builds incrementally.

185
00:12:35,064 --> 00:12:38,404
Evidence is gathered step by
step through the onboarding flow.

186
00:12:39,274 --> 00:12:44,094
Full access is unlocked only when
the stre- strong verification

187
00:12:44,754 --> 00:12:46,054
evidence is in a place.

188
00:12:46,554 --> 00:12:52,264
That gap between the one service thinks
the identity state is and another service

189
00:12:52,294 --> 00:12:56,084
assume is exactly where the policy hide.

190
00:12:56,584 --> 00:13:00,074
And this is the implementation
principles that makes progressive

191
00:13:00,114 --> 00:13:04,264
identity assurance actually works
in microservices architecture.

192
00:13:04,764 --> 00:13:05,904
The assurance level.

193
00:13:06,404 --> 00:13:11,184
The answer to how verified is this
user has to be the first-class

194
00:13:11,254 --> 00:13:13,094
part of the authentication context.

195
00:13:13,914 --> 00:13:17,164
It travels explicitly
with every service call.

196
00:13:17,654 --> 00:13:21,284
No service should have to
look it up No service should

197
00:13:21,284 --> 00:13:22,934
assume it was checked upstream.

198
00:13:23,434 --> 00:13:28,944
When verifications happen, say when
a customer uploads their ID document,

199
00:13:29,204 --> 00:13:31,714
the system emits an observable event.

200
00:13:32,644 --> 00:13:37,474
Downstream services pick up that event and
update what they allow to the users to do.

201
00:13:37,944 --> 00:13:40,984
Each step is tracked, each
state change is a record.

202
00:13:41,874 --> 00:13:46,834
For those of who building into
the code, these maps directly to

203
00:13:46,834 --> 00:13:51,034
passing the assurance level as
a typed value in your context.

204
00:13:51,534 --> 00:13:56,514
Propagate it explicitly, validate
it each boundary, never assume

205
00:13:56,544 --> 00:13:58,974
it was handled one step earlier.

206
00:13:59,474 --> 00:14:05,164
This slide title is a test I use in a
real practice, and I mean it literally.

207
00:14:05,664 --> 00:14:10,694
Auditability is not about having
logs sitting on a server somewhere.

208
00:14:11,574 --> 00:14:16,464
It is the ability to accurately
and confidently reconstruct the key

209
00:14:16,464 --> 00:14:21,644
events on demand without pulling
an engineering team, without manual

210
00:14:21,644 --> 00:14:23,704
assembly, without any guesswork.

211
00:14:24,234 --> 00:14:26,884
The system answers the
question, not the people.

212
00:14:27,674 --> 00:14:30,194
There are four properties
that makes this possible.

213
00:14:30,784 --> 00:14:31,814
Structure records.

214
00:14:32,314 --> 00:14:37,844
Not free text, but mission-readable events
with the defined structure integrity,

215
00:14:38,344 --> 00:14:40,784
timestamped, ordered, and immutable.

216
00:14:41,534 --> 00:14:43,784
Once written, unchangeable.

217
00:14:44,714 --> 00:14:45,564
Completeness.

218
00:14:46,104 --> 00:14:50,784
No gaps in the critical interaction
trail and accessibility.

219
00:14:51,494 --> 00:14:54,904
Auditors can retrieve the
records themselves independently

220
00:14:54,904 --> 00:14:56,034
without an engineer.

221
00:14:56,534 --> 00:14:59,974
The fourth one is your
practical test right now.

222
00:15:00,774 --> 00:15:04,814
Can you auditors access the evidence
they need without an engineer

223
00:15:04,814 --> 00:15:07,064
doing the attraction for them?

224
00:15:07,564 --> 00:15:10,344
If the answer is no, you have logs.

225
00:15:10,584 --> 00:15:12,494
You don't have the auditability.

226
00:15:12,994 --> 00:15:16,104
Auditability tells you
what happened at runtime.

227
00:15:16,704 --> 00:15:21,684
Traceability tells you why the
system was built the way it was and

228
00:15:21,684 --> 00:15:23,974
whether that reasoning still holds.

229
00:15:24,794 --> 00:15:29,454
Traceability is the navigable link
between the regulatory requirement,

230
00:15:29,894 --> 00:15:34,884
the design control that satisfied, and
the observable behavior of the system.

231
00:15:35,354 --> 00:15:40,754
You can start at any system behavior and
trace it all the way back to the specific

232
00:15:40,794 --> 00:15:42,784
obligation it was built to satisfy.

233
00:15:43,284 --> 00:15:45,874
Without traceability,
compliance is claimed.

234
00:15:46,524 --> 00:15:52,284
It rests on people memory, documentation
that may be out of the date, and hope.

235
00:15:53,264 --> 00:15:55,524
With traceability, compliance is proven.

236
00:15:56,354 --> 00:16:02,124
You can show the chain from regulation
to control To implementation, to

237
00:16:02,124 --> 00:16:03,924
what the system actually does.

238
00:16:04,424 --> 00:16:06,674
Two practical benefits worth naming.

239
00:16:07,134 --> 00:16:11,604
First, you can scale with confidence
when you add a new product

240
00:16:11,864 --> 00:16:13,834
or expand to the new region.

241
00:16:14,334 --> 00:16:16,534
You know immediately which controls apply.

242
00:16:17,234 --> 00:16:23,514
The second, you can predict the impact of
the change before it goes out, not after.

243
00:16:24,014 --> 00:16:28,864
Pillar three, and this is the one that
gets under underestimate most time.

244
00:16:29,834 --> 00:16:30,974
Production is messy.

245
00:16:31,424 --> 00:16:32,474
Networks drop.

246
00:16:32,954 --> 00:16:36,274
Third-party identify
verification services time out.

247
00:16:37,034 --> 00:16:39,524
Users abandon flows halfway through.

248
00:16:40,184 --> 00:16:41,854
These are not edge cases.

249
00:16:42,274 --> 00:16:45,314
They happen every time,
every day at scale.

250
00:16:45,814 --> 00:16:47,624
And here is the compliance problem.

251
00:16:48,324 --> 00:16:52,214
When a flow is interrupted,
loosely connected services diverge

252
00:16:52,214 --> 00:16:55,614
in their understanding of what
the state the customer is on.

253
00:16:56,114 --> 00:17:00,414
One service thinks they complete
verification, another thinks they did not.

254
00:17:01,284 --> 00:17:06,124
Practical computations create a
legal ambiguity, an identify state

255
00:17:06,434 --> 00:17:10,224
where it is not clear what the
customer relationship actually is.

256
00:17:10,724 --> 00:17:13,074
The example on the
screen make it concrete.

257
00:17:13,774 --> 00:17:18,724
Identity data collected, but then
the disclosure fails to show because

258
00:17:18,754 --> 00:17:20,514
a downstream service timed out.

259
00:17:21,444 --> 00:17:26,644
The customer is now in a illegally
undefined onboarded state.

260
00:17:27,154 --> 00:17:28,524
That is not a technical hiccup.

261
00:17:29,474 --> 00:17:30,854
That is the compliance problem.

262
00:17:31,354 --> 00:17:34,634
The solution pattern in
Saga-based orchestration.

263
00:17:35,504 --> 00:17:40,164
The Saga coordinate multi-step
distributed workflows by including

264
00:17:40,564 --> 00:17:45,624
compensating transactions, which
means if a step fails, the system has

265
00:17:45,624 --> 00:17:49,924
defined way to resolve the practical
work and restore a consistent state.

266
00:17:50,424 --> 00:17:52,144
The customer session is passed.

267
00:17:52,984 --> 00:17:54,944
Their practical progress is preserved.

268
00:17:55,654 --> 00:18:00,064
They are notified, and critically,
the cause of the interruption and

269
00:18:00,064 --> 00:18:02,104
resolution taken are both logged.

270
00:18:02,604 --> 00:18:05,404
The orchestration holds
the authoritative state.

271
00:18:06,164 --> 00:18:09,504
Individual services do not
need to sync with each other.

272
00:18:10,484 --> 00:18:13,034
They each report their
outcomes to the orchestrator.

273
00:18:13,844 --> 00:18:16,274
And audit requirement is clear.

274
00:18:16,844 --> 00:18:19,614
Every exception path
must produce a record.

275
00:18:19,784 --> 00:18:21,184
The failure gets logged.

276
00:18:21,684 --> 00:18:24,244
The compensation action gets logged.

277
00:18:24,744 --> 00:18:26,164
The resolution gets logged.

278
00:18:26,294 --> 00:18:30,574
Exception paths are treated with
exactly the same rigor as success paths.

279
00:18:31,074 --> 00:18:34,774
Now I want to show you how all
three pillars are connect at the

280
00:18:34,774 --> 00:18:36,654
architecture level in a single flow.

281
00:18:37,154 --> 00:18:38,144
Customer browser.

282
00:18:38,604 --> 00:18:40,619
This is where the interaction start.

283
00:18:41,259 --> 00:18:46,459
Where user action that has a compliance
im- implication as captured from here.

284
00:18:46,959 --> 00:18:48,009
Front UI layer.

285
00:18:48,509 --> 00:18:50,139
Consent flows are enforced here.

286
00:18:50,369 --> 00:18:54,819
The system cannot advance without
the consent gate being satisfied.

287
00:18:55,319 --> 00:18:56,199
Consent service.

288
00:18:56,639 --> 00:19:00,399
This is where the consent
event is created and emitted.

289
00:19:00,759 --> 00:19:03,669
It is not an UI record,
it is a system record.

290
00:19:04,169 --> 00:19:06,549
Event bus, which is typically Kafka.

291
00:19:06,989 --> 00:19:11,859
The consent event is published here
as an immutable append-only record.

292
00:19:12,359 --> 00:19:15,969
Immutable store, which
is S3, which object lock.

293
00:19:16,439 --> 00:19:18,639
The record is persisted permanently.

294
00:19:19,069 --> 00:19:21,589
It cannot be modified after it is written.

295
00:19:22,589 --> 00:19:23,689
An audit API.

296
00:19:24,439 --> 00:19:26,459
This is how auditors are authorized.

297
00:19:26,459 --> 00:19:31,489
System query the evidence directly
without engineering involvement.

298
00:19:31,989 --> 00:19:35,079
Below the flow, you can see
three compliance properties

299
00:19:35,079 --> 00:19:36,389
that each layer supports.

300
00:19:37,019 --> 00:19:40,779
The consent event, content,
and exception handling.

301
00:19:41,089 --> 00:19:42,099
The consent event.

302
00:19:42,809 --> 00:19:44,419
Versioned and immutable.

303
00:19:45,069 --> 00:19:49,579
Context propagated explicitly
across all service calls.

304
00:19:50,279 --> 00:19:51,329
Exception handling.

305
00:19:51,829 --> 00:19:56,959
Every failure is logged and
compensated by the Saga orchestrator.

306
00:19:57,459 --> 00:20:01,919
This table maps each compliance
layer to a specific technology choice

307
00:20:02,569 --> 00:20:04,619
and the reason behind the choice.

308
00:20:05,389 --> 00:20:05,959
Consent.

309
00:20:06,789 --> 00:20:09,679
The version immutable append-only records.

310
00:20:10,139 --> 00:20:14,369
Apache Kafka or AWS S3 with object lock.

311
00:20:14,939 --> 00:20:17,859
The choice is driven by the
immutability requirement.

312
00:20:18,579 --> 00:20:19,229
Identity.

313
00:20:19,849 --> 00:20:27,059
Assurance level is the propagated
auth context, AWS, OAuth, JWT claims,

314
00:20:27,899 --> 00:20:32,859
SPIFFE, and SPIRE for workload identity.

315
00:20:33,299 --> 00:20:38,009
The choice is driven by the consistency
across boundaries requirement.

316
00:20:38,509 --> 00:20:39,329
Orchestration.

317
00:20:39,829 --> 00:20:42,869
Saga-based, exception-aware
workflow management.

318
00:20:43,629 --> 00:20:46,929
AWS Step Functions and Conducto.

319
00:20:47,429 --> 00:20:52,119
Temporal specifically has excellent
Go support, which makes it a strong

320
00:20:52,119 --> 00:20:54,289
choice for teams on this stack.

321
00:20:54,789 --> 00:20:55,339
Audit log.

322
00:20:55,839 --> 00:21:00,209
That captures success and failure
and resolutions with equal details.

323
00:21:00,969 --> 00:21:05,229
OpenTelemetry, Elasticsearch, CloudTrail.

324
00:21:05,729 --> 00:21:07,629
The last, the disclosure count.

325
00:21:08,259 --> 00:21:13,649
The versioned S3 buckets or Git ba--
backend content store chosen because

326
00:21:13,729 --> 00:21:18,799
they preserve every historical version
and make any past state resolvable.

327
00:21:19,529 --> 00:21:24,549
These are not arbitrary choices Each one
is selected because of the compliance

328
00:21:24,549 --> 00:21:26,539
property it needs to be supported.

329
00:21:27,039 --> 00:21:31,329
Let me make everything concrete by
tracing through a real scenario.

330
00:21:31,939 --> 00:21:35,969
A customer opening up a saving
account in a digital bank app.

331
00:21:36,469 --> 00:21:38,959
Pillar one, consent and disclosure.

332
00:21:39,569 --> 00:21:43,849
The customer reviews the terms of
service and the GDPR disclosure.

333
00:21:44,549 --> 00:21:48,959
Every interaction is then immediately
captured as the immutable event in

334
00:21:48,959 --> 00:21:52,119
Kafka, stored in S3 with object log.

335
00:21:53,029 --> 00:21:57,589
If a regulator asks tomorrow what
the customer agreed to, the answer

336
00:21:57,589 --> 00:21:59,379
is already there immediately.

337
00:22:00,139 --> 00:22:01,699
Complete, precise.

338
00:22:02,619 --> 00:22:05,549
Pillar two, progressive
identity assurance.

339
00:22:06,379 --> 00:22:10,249
If this is email verified,
low-risk access is guaranteed.

340
00:22:10,699 --> 00:22:12,119
ID document uploaded.

341
00:22:12,769 --> 00:22:15,909
The assurance level is
updated in the JWT claims.

342
00:22:16,699 --> 00:22:18,639
Funds transfer is unlocked.

343
00:22:18,969 --> 00:22:21,119
Each state change emits an event.

344
00:22:21,349 --> 00:22:24,519
No service ever acts on old identity data.

345
00:22:25,469 --> 00:22:27,889
Pillar three, exception handling.

346
00:22:28,099 --> 00:22:30,749
The third-party KYC provider times out.

347
00:22:31,249 --> 00:22:33,379
The Saga orchestrator steps in.

348
00:22:33,849 --> 00:22:35,909
A compensating transactions run.

349
00:22:36,489 --> 00:22:37,639
The session is passed.

350
00:22:37,719 --> 00:22:39,559
The practical state is preserved.

351
00:22:40,149 --> 00:22:41,659
The customer is notified.

352
00:22:41,929 --> 00:22:44,219
The cause, the fix for both logged.

353
00:22:45,159 --> 00:22:46,439
There is no audit gap.

354
00:22:46,939 --> 00:22:49,169
So how do you actually build this?

355
00:22:49,809 --> 00:22:50,469
The five steps.

356
00:22:51,299 --> 00:22:55,499
I want to be clear that these are not
sequential phases you finish once.

357
00:22:56,069 --> 00:23:00,809
They are ongoing practices that you
build into how your teams works.

358
00:23:01,429 --> 00:23:02,429
Step one, map.

359
00:23:02,929 --> 00:23:07,299
Identify your re-regulatory
obligations and map them into the

360
00:23:07,299 --> 00:23:11,109
specific customer interactions where
those obligations are triggered.

361
00:23:12,039 --> 00:23:13,449
Not at a general level.

362
00:23:13,959 --> 00:23:18,429
At the level of at this exact
interaction point in this specific flow,

363
00:23:19,019 --> 00:23:20,969
these three obligations are active.

364
00:23:21,809 --> 00:23:23,599
Step two, translate.

365
00:23:24,079 --> 00:23:28,049
Take each obligations and convert
it into the concrete architectural

366
00:23:28,049 --> 00:23:30,709
constraint, something the system enforces.

367
00:23:31,619 --> 00:23:37,189
If consent is required, the constraint is
the system cannot proceed past this point

368
00:23:37,359 --> 00:23:39,559
without a consent event being recorded.

369
00:23:40,559 --> 00:23:42,269
Step three, instrument.

370
00:23:43,199 --> 00:23:48,649
Embedded evidence generations into your
workflow, your APIs and your system

371
00:23:48,649 --> 00:23:51,069
boundaries as a first-class outputs.

372
00:23:51,549 --> 00:23:53,109
This is not a logging exercise.

373
00:23:53,219 --> 00:23:57,519
It is designed output built into
the flow, not added on top of it.

374
00:23:58,349 --> 00:24:00,259
Step four, validate.

375
00:24:01,019 --> 00:24:04,559
Test auditability and traceability
as functional requirement.

376
00:24:05,039 --> 00:24:06,869
They go into the test suit.

377
00:24:07,399 --> 00:24:09,339
They have acceptance criteria.

378
00:24:09,799 --> 00:24:11,994
They fail the build if they are not met.

379
00:24:12,494 --> 00:24:13,874
Auditability is a feature.

380
00:24:13,984 --> 00:24:15,024
Treat it like one.

381
00:24:15,714 --> 00:24:17,734
Step five, governor.

382
00:24:18,294 --> 00:24:22,424
E-est-establish the change
control practices that protect

383
00:24:22,424 --> 00:24:25,594
your compliance critical
components as the platform scales.

384
00:24:26,154 --> 00:24:30,934
Not everything needs a compliance gate,
but the right things must have one.

385
00:24:31,434 --> 00:24:35,774
My honest recommendation on
where to start, do not try to

386
00:24:35,774 --> 00:24:37,504
do this everywhere at once.

387
00:24:38,334 --> 00:24:42,404
Pick your single highest risk
customer integration, the one

388
00:24:42,404 --> 00:24:47,574
that if a regulator asked about it
tomorrow would worry you the most.

389
00:24:48,074 --> 00:24:52,344
Make that one flow fully
explainable, then you have the

390
00:24:52,344 --> 00:24:54,924
pattern, then you have scale it.

391
00:24:55,424 --> 00:25:01,124
Let me make the outcome concrete because
a compliance architecture can sound like a

392
00:25:01,124 --> 00:25:03,804
lot of investment for an abstract benefit.

393
00:25:04,304 --> 00:25:08,034
Audits that used to take weeks
of manual assembly get answered

394
00:25:08,034 --> 00:25:13,084
in hours because the records are
already there, structured, queryable.

395
00:25:13,584 --> 00:25:18,894
Disputes get resolved which verify
evidence instead of contents to memories.

396
00:25:19,584 --> 00:25:20,554
No war rooms.

397
00:25:20,784 --> 00:25:24,094
Regulator reviews handles
without mobilizing the entire

398
00:25:24,094 --> 00:25:26,604
engineering team in emergency mode.

399
00:25:27,104 --> 00:25:31,974
And the one that consistently surprise
people, engineering team actually move

400
00:25:31,974 --> 00:25:34,824
faster because compliance is built-in.

401
00:25:35,404 --> 00:25:39,144
They are not stopping to
retrofit it after every release.

402
00:25:39,644 --> 00:25:41,444
One thought to close with.

403
00:25:41,944 --> 00:25:43,684
Compliance is not a project phase.

404
00:25:43,984 --> 00:25:47,954
It is a structural quality
reliability, like security.

405
00:25:48,704 --> 00:25:51,524
It either holds under
pressure or it does not.

406
00:25:52,254 --> 00:25:58,344
And whether it holds depends entirely on
whether it was designed into the platform

407
00:25:58,504 --> 00:26:03,684
from the beginning or added on top of
the decision that were already made.

408
00:26:04,184 --> 00:26:07,134
Start with your highest
risk customer interactions.

409
00:26:07,374 --> 00:26:13,015
Ma-make it explainable, then scale that
principle across your entire platform.

410
00:26:13,515 --> 00:26:14,585
Thank you so much.

411
00:26:15,065 --> 00:26:16,525
Thank you for watching.

412
00:26:17,085 --> 00:26:21,075
I am Manasa Uppala, Enterprise
Web Architect and independent

413
00:26:21,075 --> 00:26:22,865
research based in the USA.

414
